# Impeccable Code Standards

## TypeScript

- Prefer explicit return types on all exported functions and hooks
- Never use `any`; use `unknown` and narrow, or define a proper type/interface
- Use `type` for unions/intersections, `interface` for object shapes
- Always destructure props inline; never accept a single `props` object without destructuring

```typescript
// ❌
function foo(props: any) { return props.value }

// ✅
function foo({ value }: { value: string }): string { return value }
```

## React Components

- Functional components only; no class components
- One component per file; filename matches the exported component name
- Extract logic into custom hooks (`use*.ts`) when a component exceeds ~80 lines or logic is reusable
- Never inline complex JSX — break it into named sub-components or variables
- Keep `useEffect` minimal; prefer derived state and memoization over effects

```tsx
// ❌ — logic and markup tangled together
export default function Panel() {
  const [data, setData] = useState([])
  useEffect(() => { fetch('/api').then(r => r.json()).then(setData) }, [])
  return <ul>{data.map(d => <li key={d.id}>{d.name}</li>)}</ul>
}

// ✅
export default function Panel() {
  const data = useData()
  return <DataList items={data} />
}
```

## Zustand State (resumeStore)

- Access only the slices you need — never select the entire store object
- Derive values inside selectors, not inside components
- Mutations belong in the store's actions, never inline in components

```typescript
// ❌
const store = useResumeStore()
const name = store.resume.contact.name

// ✅
const name = useResumeStore(s => s.resume.contact.name)
```

## Performance

- Wrap expensive computations in `useMemo`; wrap stable callbacks passed to children in `useCallback`
- Avoid creating objects/arrays as default prop values or in render scope — define them outside or memoize
- Prefer CSS/Tailwind transitions over JS-driven animations for UI feedback

## Code Style & Naming

- Components: `PascalCase`
- Hooks, utilities, variables: `camelCase`
- Types/interfaces: `PascalCase`
- Constants: `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` only for true module-level constants
- Boolean props/variables: prefix with `is`, `has`, or `can` (e.g. `isOpen`, `hasError`)

## Comments

- No comments that restate what the code does
- Only comment to explain **why** something non-obvious was done, or to document a constraint/trade-off
- Remove all TODO/FIXME comments before considering a task complete
